Credit Card Users Churn Prediction¶

Problem Statement¶

Business Context¶

The Thera bank recently saw a steep decline in the number of users of their credit card, credit cards are a good source of income for banks because of different kinds of fees charged by the banks like annual fees, balance transfer fees, and cash advance fees, late payment fees, foreign transaction fees, and others. Some fees are charged to every user irrespective of usage, while others are charged under specified circumstances.

Customers’ leaving credit cards services would lead bank to loss, so the bank wants to analyze the data of customers and identify the customers who will leave their credit card services and reason for same – so that bank could improve upon those areas

You as a Data scientist at Thera bank need to come up with a classification model that will help the bank improve its services so that customers do not renounce their credit cards

Data Description¶

  • CLIENTNUM: Client number. Unique identifier for the customer holding the account
  • Attrition_Flag: Internal event (customer activity) variable - if the account is closed then "Attrited Customer" else "Existing Customer"
  • Customer_Age: Age in Years
  • Gender: Gender of the account holder
  • Dependent_count: Number of dependents
  • Education_Level: Educational Qualification of the account holder - Graduate, High School, Unknown, Uneducated, College(refers to college student), Post-Graduate, Doctorate
  • Marital_Status: Marital Status of the account holder
  • Income_Category: Annual Income Category of the account holder
  • Card_Category: Type of Card
  • Months_on_book: Period of relationship with the bank (in months)
  • Total_Relationship_Count: Total no. of products held by the customer
  • Months_Inactive_12_mon: No. of months inactive in the last 12 months
  • Contacts_Count_12_mon: No. of Contacts in the last 12 months
  • Credit_Limit: Credit Limit on the Credit Card
  • Total_Revolving_Bal: Total Revolving Balance on the Credit Card
  • Avg_Open_To_Buy: Open to Buy Credit Line (Average of last 12 months)
  • Total_Amt_Chng_Q4_Q1: Change in Transaction Amount (Q4 over Q1)
  • Total_Trans_Amt: Total Transaction Amount (Last 12 months)
  • Total_Trans_Ct: Total Transaction Count (Last 12 months)
  • Total_Ct_Chng_Q4_Q1: Change in Transaction Count (Q4 over Q1)
  • Avg_Utilization_Ratio: Average Card Utilization Ratio

What Is a Revolving Balance?¶

  • If we don't pay the balance of the revolving credit account in full every month, the unpaid portion carries over to the next month. That's called a revolving balance
What is the Average Open to buy?¶
  • 'Open to Buy' means the amount left on your credit card to use. Now, this column represents the average of this value for the last 12 months.
What is the Average utilization Ratio?¶
  • The Avg_Utilization_Ratio represents how much of the available credit the customer spent. This is useful for calculating credit scores.
Relation b/w Avg_Open_To_Buy, Credit_Limit and Avg_Utilization_Ratio:¶
  • ( Avg_Open_To_Buy / Credit_Limit ) + Avg_Utilization_Ratio = 1

Observation¶

  • There are 10127 rows and 21 columns in the dataset
  • CLIENTNUM is an unique identifier which can be dropped
  • Customer_Age,Dependent_Count,Months_on_book, Total_Relationship_Count,Months_Inactive_12_mon,Contacts_Count_12_Mon, Credit_Limit, Total_Revolving_Bal, Avg_Open_To_Buy, Total_Amt_CHNG_Q4_Q1, Total_Trans_Amt, Total_Trans_Ct, Total_Ct_Chng_Q4_Q1, Avg_Utilization_Ratio are numerical features in the data set
  • Gender, Marital_Status are nominal categorical features in the dataset
  • Education_level, Card_Category and Income_Category are also categorical features. These could be treated as ordinal type
  • Education_level feature has missing value for 1519 rows. These customers might have chosen not to share this information. We will label it as "Unknown" where this information is missing.
  • Marital_Status feature has missing value for 749 rows. These customers might have chosen not to share this information. We will label it as "Unknown" where this information is missing.
  • Dataset doesn't have any duplicate row
  • Attrition_Flag is our target variable and it has following classes

     Existing Customer: Account is open for these customers
    Attrited Customer: Account is closed for these customers
Our goal is to build machine learning models so we can predict whether a customer will be attrited(Negative outcome) or will not be attrited(Positive outcome). Through our analysis we will also try to identify possible reasons for attrition so Thera Bank can address those concerns.

Exploratory Data Analysis (EDA)¶

  • EDA is an important part of any project involving data.
  • It is important to investigate and understand the data better before building a model with it.
  • A few questions have been mentioned below which will help you approach the analysis in the right manner and generate insights from the data.
  • A thorough analysis of the data, in addition to the questions mentioned below, should be done.

Questions:

  1. How is the total transaction amount distributed?

Ans: Total_Trans_Amt has multimodal distribution with positive skewness due to outliers. We observe 4 different groups of customers with different spending behaviours. The average transaction amount is around \$4400. Though we have 896 customers who have spent around \$8619 or more in the last 12 month, 75% of customers have spent around \$4741 or less.

  1. What is the distribution of the level of education of customers?

Ans: Most customers are gradulate level educated 30.9%, followed by High School educated 19.9%. 14.7% customers are uneducated and the education level is unknown for 15% customers.

  1. What is the distribution of the level of income of customers?

Ans: Income_Category had intially 6 classes, labelled as $120k +, 40k-60k, 60k-80k, 80k-120k, Less than $40k and abc. The abc could be customers who didn't share their income data. We changed this class to Unknown. We observed 35.2% customers have income less than \$40k, followed by 17.7% have income between 40k-60k. 7.2% customers earn more than \$120k and we don't have income data for 11% customers.

  1. How does the change in transaction amount between Q4 and Q1 (total_ct_change_Q4_Q1) vary by the customer's account status (Attrition_Flag)?

Ans: 75% existing customers reducing the number of transactions at least by 16.7% in Q4 compared to Q1, where as, 75% attrited customer reducing the number of transactions at least by 30.8% in Q4 compared to Q1.

  1. How does the number of months a customer was inactive in the last 12 months (Months_Inactive_12_mon) vary by the customer's account status (Attrition_Flag)?

Ans: 75% customers who attrited were inactive at least 2 months or more in the last 12 month, where as, the customers who stayed were inactive at least 1 month or more. There are some outliers for attrited customers. 51 attrited customers were inactive more than 4 months. There are 15 attrited customers who were not inactive over the 12 months.

  1. What are the attributes that have a strong correlation with each other?

Ans: Months_on_book has strong positive correlation with Customer_Age. Credit_Limit has the strogest postive correlation of 1 with Avg_Open_To_Buy. Total_Trans_Amt has strong postive correlation with Total_Trans_CT. Avg_Utilization_Ratio has moderate postive correlation with Total_Revolving_Bal.
Credit_Limit has moderate negative correlation with Avg_Utilization_Ratio. Avg_Open_To_Buy has moderate negative correlation with Avg_Utilization_Ratio.
From the Chi-squared test we observed that Gender and Income_category has an effect on our target variable Attrition_Flag

# function to plot a boxplot and a histogram along the same scale.


def histogram_boxplot(data, feature, figsize=(12, 7), kde=False, bins=None):
    """
    Boxplot and histogram combined

    data: dataframe
    feature: dataframe column
    figsize: size of figure (default (12,7))
    kde: whether to the show density curve (default False)
    bins: number of bins for histogram (default None)
    """
    f2, (ax_box2, ax_hist2) = plt.subplots(
        nrows=2,  # Number of rows of the subplot grid= 2
        sharex=True,  # x-axis will be shared among all subplots
        gridspec_kw={"height_ratios": (0.25, 0.75)},
        figsize=figsize,
    )  # creating the 2 subplots
    sns.boxplot(
        data=data, x=feature, ax=ax_box2, showmeans=True, color="violet"
    )  # boxplot will be created and a triangle will indicate the mean value of the column
    sns.histplot(
        data=data, x=feature, kde=kde, ax=ax_hist2, bins=bins, palette="winter"
    ) if bins else sns.histplot(
        data=data, x=feature, kde=kde, ax=ax_hist2
    )  # For histogram
    ax_hist2.axvline(
        data[feature].mean(), color="green", linestyle="--"
    )  # Add mean to the histogram
    ax_hist2.axvline(
        data[feature].median(), color="black", linestyle="-"
    )  # Add median to the histogram

# function to create labeled barplots


def labeled_barplot(data, feature, perc=False, n=None):
    """
    Barplot with percentage at the top

    data: dataframe
    feature: dataframe column
    perc: whether to display percentages instead of count (default is False)
    n: displays the top n category levels (default is None, i.e., display all levels)
    """

    total = len(data[feature])  # length of the column
    count = data[feature].nunique()
    if n is None:
        plt.figure(figsize=(count + 1, 5))
    else:
        plt.figure(figsize=(n + 1, 5))

    plt.xticks(rotation=90, fontsize=15)
    ax = sns.countplot(
        data=data,
        x=feature,
        palette="Paired",
        order=data[feature].value_counts().index[:n].sort_values(),
    )

    for p in ax.patches:
        if perc == True:
            label = "{:.1f}%".format(
                100 * p.get_height() / total
            )  # percentage of each class of the category
        else:
            label = p.get_height()  # count of each level of the category

        x = p.get_x() + p.get_width() / 2  # width of the plot
        y = p.get_height()  # height of the plot

        ax.annotate(
            label,
            (x, y),
            ha="center",
            va="center",
            size=12,
            xytext=(0, 5),
            textcoords="offset points",
        )  # annotate the percentage

    plt.show()  # show the plot
In [144]:
# function to plot stacked bar chart

def stacked_barplot(data, predictor, target):
    """
    Print the category counts and plot a stacked bar chart

    data: dataframe
    predictor: independent variable
    target: target variable
    """
    count = data[predictor].nunique()
    sorter = data[target].value_counts().index[-1]
    tab1 = pd.crosstab(data[predictor], data[target], margins=True).sort_values(
        by=sorter, ascending=False
    )
    print(tab1)
    print("-" * 120)
    tab = pd.crosstab(data[predictor], data[target], normalize="index").sort_values(
        by=sorter, ascending=False
    )
    tab.plot(kind="bar", stacked=True, figsize=(count + 1, 5))
    plt.legend(
        loc="lower left", frameon=False,
    )
    plt.legend(loc="upper left", bbox_to_anchor=(1, 1))
    plt.show()

### Function to plot distributions

def distribution_plot_wrt_target(data, predictor, target):

    fig, axs = plt.subplots(2, 2, figsize=(12, 10))

    target_uniq = data[target].unique()

    axs[0, 0].set_title(f"Distribution of {predictor} vs {str(target_uniq[0])}")
    sns.histplot(
        data=data[data[target] == target_uniq[0]],
        x=predictor,
        kde=True,
        ax=axs[0, 0],
        color="teal",
    )

    axs[0, 1].set_title(f"Distribution of {predictor} vs {str(target_uniq[1])}")
    sns.histplot(
        data=data[data[target] == target_uniq[1]],
        x=predictor,
        kde=True,
        ax=axs[0, 1],
        color="orange",
    )

    axs[1, 0].set_title(f"Boxplot - target vs {predictor}")
    sns.boxplot(data=data, x=target, y=predictor, ax=axs[1, 0], palette="gist_rainbow")

    axs[1, 1].set_title(f"Boxplot (without outliers) - target vs {predictor}")
    sns.boxplot(
        data=data,
        x=target,
        y=predictor,
        ax=axs[1, 1],
        showfliers=False,
        palette="gist_rainbow",
    )

    plt.tight_layout()
    plt.show()

We have changed this class to Unknown. Correlation Analysis (Chi-squared test for categorical data)¶

In [162]:
def chi_square_test(data, predictor, target):
  crosstab = pd.crosstab(data[predictor], data[target])
  Ho = f"{predictor} has no effect on {target}"  # Stating the Null Hypothesis
  Ha = f"{predictor} has an effect on {target}"  # Stating the Alternate Hypothesis

  chi, p_value, dof, expected = stats.chi2_contingency(crosstab)

  if p_value < 0.05:  # Setting our significance level at 5%
      print(f"{Ha} as the p_value ({p_value.round(3)}) < 0.05")
  else:
      print(f"{Ho} as the p_value ({p_value.round(3)}) > 0.05")

Model Building¶

Model evaluation criterion¶

The nature of predictions made by the classification model will translate as follows:

  • True positives (TP) are attrited customers correctly predicted by the model.
  • True negative (TN) are staying customers correctly predicted by the model
  • False negatives (FN) are attrited customers that the model incorrectly predicts as staying.
  • False positives (FP) are staying customers but the model incorrectly predicts as attrited.

Which metric to optimize?

  • We would want Recall to be maximized as greater the Recall, the higher the chances of minimizing false negatives.
  • We want to minimize false negatives. Because a model incorrectly predicting a customer will stay means the bank will fail to take step to convince that customer and it will loose revenue.

Let's define a function to output different metrics (including recall) on the train and test set and a function to show confusion matrix so that we do not have to use the same code repetitively while evaluating models.

In [179]:
# defining a function to compute different metrics to check performance of a classification model built using sklearn
def model_performance_classification_sklearn(model, predictors, target, index = [0]):
    """
    Function to compute different metrics to check classification model performance

    model: classifier
    predictors: independent variables
    target: dependent variable
    """

    # predicting using the independent variables
    pred = model.predict(predictors)

    acc = accuracy_score(target, pred)  # to compute Accuracy
    recall = recall_score(target, pred)  # to compute Recall
    precision = precision_score(target, pred)  # to compute Precision
    f1 = f1_score(target, pred)  # to compute F1-score

    # creating a dataframe of metrics
    df_perf = pd.DataFrame(
        {
            "Accuracy": acc,
            "Recall": recall,
            "Precision": precision,
            "F1": f1

        },
        index=index,
    )

    return df_perf

    kfold = StratifiedKFold(
        n_splits=5, shuffle=True, random_state=1
    )  # Setting number of splits equal to 5
    cv_result = cross_val_score(
        estimator=model, X=X_train, y=y_train, scoring=scoring, cv=kfold
    )
    mean_recall_score = cv_result.mean()
    results[name + ' (no sampling)'] = mean_recall_score

    model.fit(X_train, y_train)

Observations¶

  • The tuned XGBoost model with undersampled dataset has the best recall score 99.6% in the validation set. This model has recall score 100% in training dataset.
  • It has 75.5% accuracy, 39.6% precision and 56.7% F1 score.
  • It is appearant that the tuned XGBoost model with undersample data, highly prioritize minimizing the false negative prediction. A false negative prediction will predict a customer wouldn't close the account even though the customer would have closed it. Increased false negative prediction would increase loss for the bank.
  • Therefore, improving the recall is the right thing for this use case even though it comes at the cost of lower precision and F1 score.
  • Based on the above, XGBoost with undersampled dataset is our final selected model.

Business Insights and Conclusions¶

  • From our data analysis we observed that customers who decided to close their accounts having less number of transactions. It is worth particularly looking at why customers are reducing transactions. Are there competitors who are offering better deal e.g. cashback, balance transfer etc
  • We also noticed customers who decided to close thier accounts had reduced avg. transaction amounts over the last 12 month. This could be due to the affordability of the particular credit card or better deal available with competitors.
  • Our analysis shows 25% customers who attrited have revolving balance 0. This behaviour could be due to high interest charges which eventually might lead the customer to find a better deal with competitors.
  • The attrition rate is higher among female customers, it is worth investigating what is the root cause of it. Are competitors offering better incentive for feamle customers e.g. discount in beauty products when purchased using their card.
  • Our analysis shows that the bank has relatively small number of Gold and Platinum credit card holders and the attrition rate is high among those customers. Low adoption of high tier credit card and high attrition rate among those card holders indicate those cards are probably not meeting customers' expectation.
  • The bank has large number of customers around 35% who are earning below 40k, and attrition rate among those customers is 17.1%. It is worth investigating why these demographic of customers tend to close their credit card account.
  • Attrited customers made more contacts than those customers who didn't. Also our analysis showed customers who closed their credit card account are likely to have less number of products with the bank. Its worth investigating whether there is a link between overall customer satisfaction and customer attrition.
  • We observed both existing and attrited customers are spending less and reducing number of transactions in Q4 compared to Q1. 75% attrited customers reduced their number of transactions by 30% in Q4. It is worth finding out whether the competitors are offering better incentive in Q4 that led these customers to switch. Bank could consider incentivise Q4 spending with offers if that helps to generate more revenue.
